      "scientific": "Muntingia calabura",
      "common": "Jamaican Cherry",
      "khmer": "ដើមក្រខុប",
      "genus": "Muntingia",
      "nickname": "PLACEHOLDER",
      "image": "image/catalogue/3.jpg",
      "map": "map.html#tree-3",
      "mapX": 14.9,
      "mapY": 77.9,
      "description": "With blossoms often mistaken for those of strawberry plants, the Jamaican Cherry tree has long been another popular snack of Cambodians. The trees are resilient and can often be found by roadsides, with blooms and fruit all year round. The fruit is sweet, comparable to the taste of cotton candy or caramel, with several thousands of tiny yellow seeds inside. Fun fact: Jamaican cherries have no relation to common cherries!",
      "cite": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Muntingia_calabura",
      "id": "3"
    },
    {
      "scientific": "Samanea saman",
      "common": "Monkey Pod Tree",
      "khmer": "ដើមចាន់គិរី​/ដើមចាន់រុី",
      "genus": "Samanea",
      "nickname": "PLACEHOLDER",
      "image": "image/catalogue/4.jpg",
      "map": "map.html#tree-4",
      "mapX": 39,
      "mapY": 61.5,
      "description": "A common source of shade from the grueling sun, the Monkey Pod Tree is a more rurally-found tree in Cambodia. A massive tree commonly used as a local gathering place, it can reach up to heights of 15-25 meters, with canopy diameters of up to 61 meters. Timber and shade have been the most common uses for this tree. Fun fact: it directs water to its roots by folding up its leaves at night, allowing rainwater to fall straight down.",
      "cite": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samanea_saman",
      "id": "4"
    },
    {
      "scientific": "Artocarpus heterophyllus",
      "common": "Jackfruit",
      "khmer": "ដើមខ្នុរ",
      "genus": "Artocarpus",
      "nickname": "PLACEHOLDER",
      "image": "image/catalogue/5.jpg",
      "map": "map.html#tree-5",
      "mapX": 21.8,
      "mapY": 77.3,
      "description": "Its most popular use being in Khmer cuisine, the jackfruit is a resilient tree that thrives best in hot, tropical climates. Being able to produce up to 200-500 fruits per year, this tree’s uses have been prevalent and diverse in Cambodia, both in traditional medicine and in local cuisines. Fun Fact: this tree is renowned for its fruit, which are considered the largest tree-born fruit in the world!",
      "cite": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Artocarpus_heterophyllus",
      "id": "5"
    },
    {
      "scientific": "Alstonia scholaris",
      "common": "Blackboard Tree",
      "khmer": "ដើមអំបែងថ្ងៃ",
      "genus": "Alstonia",
      "nickname": "PLACEHOLDER",
      "image": "image/catalogue/6.jpg",
      "map": "map.html#tree-6",
      "mapX": 47.9,
      "mapY": 35.5,
      "description": "A common sight across schools in Cambodia, the Blackboard tree is one that has contributed largely to the country’s education. Called so because of its popular use as wood for blackboards and whiteboards, this tree symbolizes knowledge, wisdom, and protection. Despite this, it has also been feared for its size and the saccharine sweet fragrance of its flowers, which have been believed to cause hallucinations or attract malevolent spirits. Fun fact: It goes by another name: “The Devil’s Tree”.",
      "cite": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alstonia_scholaris",
      "id": "6"
    },
